      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Private ¶  ¶ I feel quite touched with your great consideration and kindness, dear Mr Guilfoyle, in giving me an opportunity to join in the very auspicious and promising enterprise detailed in your dr...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">70.00.00</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>William<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Guilfoyle</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS 439c, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; "/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M does not indicate whether he is writing to<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>William<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Guilfoyle or his<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>father,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Michael. However, M's reference to 'your<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>father's and your able management'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>indicates that he was addressing the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>son.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Michael Guilfoyle<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>was<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>at the time<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>trying to float a company to erect a sugar mill near his property in the Tweed River district in northern NSW.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The letter is dated to 1870 because<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Michael<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Guilfoyle seems to have conceived the idea of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>growing sugar cane and<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>erecting a mill soon after he settled at the Tweed in November 1869.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>See R. Pescott (1974), pp. 55-6.</p>
               </note>Private</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I feel quite touched with your great consideration and kindness, dear Mr Guilfoyle, in giving me an opportunity to join in the very auspicious and promising enterprise detailed in your draft prospectus.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Prospectus not found.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>My wordly<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>worldly?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>affairs however have gone under the present administration of the Ministry here entirely to ruin, and as since my early orphanage I have never yet incurred debts or monetary obligations, I am now also unable, after all my property (some years ago considerable) is gone, to share in your enterprise, feeling however that under your fathers and your able management it will become a source of lucrative prosperity to you all.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I will show the prospectus to such wealthy and speculative friends, as I may see soon.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Dicksonias of the Tweed,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Tweed River, NSW.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of which you sent fragments &amp; fronds, is Dicksonia Youngiana of Moore, Sir Will Hooker and Mr Baker regard it as identical with D. squarrosa Sw.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of N. Zealand.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>W. Hooker &amp; Baker (1865-8) (i.e. December 1866, see p. 482), p. 51, cite D<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">. youngiae</seg> as a MS name by Charles Moore and slightly paraphrase part of Moore's descriptive label<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(K 1090426), but treat it as a synonym of <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">D. squarrosa</seg>. Moore used <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">D. youngii</seg> on the specimen label and when he sent specimens to the nurseryman Veitch of Chelsea. Veitch showed the species using Moore's name at a Royal Horticultural Society event on 21 March 1865 (<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Proceedings of the Royal Horticultural Society London</seg>, vol. 5 (1865),<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>p. 66, reporting that it was 'named as a compliment to Sir Charles (sic) Young'. However, the descriptive label at Kew ends with a dedication, 'Believing this to be a new species I have named in honour of Lady Young the wife of the Governor'; thus Hooker &amp; Baker have changed the word ending to that appropriate for a female dedicatee.</p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Baker (1868), p. 14 treats <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">D. youngiae</seg> as a variety of <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">D. squarrosa</seg>, and in the second edition of W. Hooker &amp; Baker (1874), p. 461<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>it is considered a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>distinct<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>species.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I think myself, that both are varieties of one species, but I have had no chance of examining either in their native locality.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Pittosporum like tree is my Emmenospermum alphitonoides<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Described as<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Emmenosperma<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">alphitonoides</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>B62.09.01, p. 63.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(among Rhamnaceae) or an allied species. Your specimen is not sufficient for identification</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>[…]<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn6" n="7">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>An unknown amount of text missing. A page of the MS has been torn off. A small part of a marginal<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>addition<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>by M can be seen at the edge on the torn side and the remaining MS carries the marginal<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>addition<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>by M: '[…] advise to Dr Hooker'.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Dicksonia<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>squarrosa</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Dicksonia youngiana</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Emmenospermum alphitonoides</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Pittosporum</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Rhamnaceae</p>
         </div>
      </body>
